üí•SPARTAN RACE TRAINING üí•
Tip 3 of 5: strengthen your core!!
.
One of the main jobs of your core is to resist motion. The ability to do so during a spartan race or a practice or game is crucial for optimal performance and reducing the risk of injury. .
While endless crunches and sit-ups aren't a complete waste of time, training the body to resist motion is extremely important because it is what we want to do during most athletic competitions or races.
.
2 of my favorite core stability exercises include the Pallof Press and the Weighted Plank.
.
Try incorporating these into your workout 2-3x per week and let me know what you think!

üîπADHERENCE IS A MAJOR üîë FOR RESULTSüîπ
----------------------------------------------------
Similar to the nutrition pyramid posted yesterday, here is @helms3dmj pyramid for Muscle & Strength Training. 
Adherence to an exercise program is the single most important thing in order to get results. You can have a great training plan with meticulously planned out sets, reps, and rest periods, but if you constantly miss workouts you are likely leaving results on the table. Many people jump from training plan to training plan in search of the perfect one. While variables such as exercise selection and progression are very important (especially for more advanced athletes), beginners will benefit most by sticking to an exercise plan and seeing it all the way through, even if it may not be an ideal plan for them üëäüèº

.
üîπYOU LOSE WEIGHT IN A CALORIC DEFICITüîπ
----------------------------------------------------
When trying to lose weight, energy balance (calories in vs. calories out) will trump everything else. You can eat organic "clean" foods 100% of the time and still be overweightüôà
Your body cannot tell the difference between a Sweet Potato carb and a chocolate chip cookie carb. Of course ü•î are more nutrient-dense than üç™but the two are negligible when it comes to fat loss. Your body doesn't recognize Oreos and say, "this is an Oreo carb so it will be stored as fat."
Also, notice how supplements are at the üîù of the pyramid. Supplements will account for AT MOST 3% of your results! No amount of apple cider vinegar or üçã water can save you if you have a positive energy balance.

data.text: @quantum_sp I got a question, using the example stated in your post, a sweet potato vs an Oreo cookie, what would be the hormonal response to each? Which would cause a greater insulin spike?

@rayzorfit great question! When eaten alone (without the addition of any other foods or drinks), Oreos would of course cause a greater insulin spike. However, it has been proven that the glycemic index does not hold true unless foods are eaten mutually exclusive.  The main thing that I was going for with this post was to explain how diets do not have to be so restrictive and that you can eat a cookie once in a while while staying on track and not feeling guilty. Of course, I would always recommend that someone eat more nutrient-dense foods over less nutrient-dense foods, but for many people, a flexible approach like this will be more sustainable in the long-term.
